<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,620,1547]" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,297,620,647]" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">Description.</emphasis>
Head, 1 
<superScript attach="left" box="[397,408,620,634]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">st</superScript>
antennal segment and callar region reddish brown. 4 
<superScript attach="left" box="[1026,1039,620,634]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">th</superScript>
antennal segment black. Posterior part of pronotum and collar yellowish brown; median line on posterior pronotal lobe dark brown. Scutellum black, clavus yellowish brown; corium light yellowish brown, the medial part always darkened in contrast to the apical and basal portions. Membrane light yellowish brown, nearly covered with fused blackish brown patches. Legs and remaining segments of antennae yellowish brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,620,1547]" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">
Head with distinct erect hairs nearly as long as eye’s width. Labium reaching between hind coxae. Pronotum moderately declivent, flat. Anterior part of pronotum with erect hairs. Anterior half of the posterior pronotal lobe with a groove, the posterior end of the mid-line not terminated into a tubercle, posterolateral angle flat (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 9–16" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1961,1986]" captionTargetBox="[279,1309,192,1920]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[269,1319,181,1935]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 9–16. Malcus spp., pronotum dorsal and frontal views: 9 &amp; 10, M. alatus sp. nov.; 11 &amp; 12, M. bacillus sp. nov.; 13 &amp; 14, M. planus sp. nov.; 15 &amp; 16, M. externus sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3735943" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3735943/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">Figs. 13 &amp;14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,620,1547]" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">
Abdominal laterotergites V and VI very minute, laterotergite V almost invisible, laterotergite VI only represented by a serrate tooth, laterotergite VII trapezoidal, margin with finely and regular teeth (
<figureCitation box="[1208,1293,981,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–20" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1978,2003]" captionTargetBox="[211,1376,533,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[200,1388,525,1954]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 17–20. Malcus spp., abdominal laterotergites V, VI &amp; VII, ventral views: 17, M. alatus sp. nov.; 18, M. bacillus sp. nov.; 19, M. planus sp. nov.; 20, M. externus sp. nov." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3735945" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3735945/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
). Membrane large, considerably surpassing the tip of abdomen.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,620,1547]" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">
Pygophore of normal shape without parandria, narrowing posteriorly, distal margin slightly convex (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 21–30" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1955,1980]" captionTargetBox="[229,1359,181,1918]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[229,1359,181,1930]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 21–30. Malcus spp., pygophore, ventral views: 21 &amp; 25, M. planus sp. nov.; 22 &amp; 26, M. externus sp. nov.; 23 &amp; 27, M. bacillus sp. nov.; 24 &amp; 28, M. gibbus Zheng, Zou &amp; Hsiao; 29, M. auriculatus Štys; 30, M. inconspicuus Štys." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3735947" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3735947/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">Figs. 21, 25</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,620,1547]" box="[199,625,1125,1151]" pageId="6" pageNumber="37">
